g is informed by discourses that use language, forms, and styles different from—and at times at odds with—the mainstream. She explores the ways in which educators can focus not simply on what they believe kids need to be taught, but also on what makes them want to learn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aEducation : Curriculum. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Literacy Studies. 4aEducation : Urban Education. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842658740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438426587423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438426587/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles